WEBVTT

00:01.360 --> 00:04.466
Sherlock!
I'm heading to the precinct.

00:08.540 --> 00:11.361
Watson, you know Everyone.

00:11.410 --> 00:13.605
Actually, I don't
know anyone.

00:13.640 --> 00:15.198
No, I mean Everyone
with a capital "E."

00:15.240 --> 00:16.309
The hacker collective.

00:16.350 --> 00:19.376
These are six of
theIr members.

00:19.420 --> 00:21.547
And what are they doing
in our living room?

00:21.580 --> 00:23.138
They've come to help
with your clothing drive

00:23.190 --> 00:24.748
for Haven for
the Homeless.

00:24.790 --> 00:27.258
I've just helped them out of a
spot of bother with the NSA,

00:27.290 --> 00:28.382
and they owe me.

00:30.360 --> 00:33.249
That's really great,
but...

00:35.400 --> 00:37.061
Um, what are they doing?

00:37.100 --> 00:39.261
They are giving you
their clothing.

00:39.300 --> 00:40.790
When they help me,
they collect payment

00:40.840 --> 00:42.501
by asking me to
humiliate myself,

00:42.540 --> 00:44.428
so fair's fair,
is it not?

00:47.840 --> 00:51.105
Okay, all of this is
gonna have to be washed.

00:51.150 --> 00:52.742
Yup.

00:52.780 --> 00:54.475
Does your charity
require undergarments?

00:54.520 --> 00:56.488
(door opens, closes)

00:56.520 --> 00:59.455
Better safe than sorry, no?

00:59.490 --> 01:01.378
BELL:
Got one more batch for you.

01:01.420 --> 01:03.388
Oh, great. You can just
put it right there. Thanks.

01:03.430 --> 01:04.727
Mm-hmm.

01:04.760 --> 01:07.490
Who knew cops
could be so generous?

01:07.530 --> 01:08.622
This is the fourth
clothing drive

01:08.660 --> 01:10.161
I_'ve done here
In four years,

01:10.200 --> 01:12.168
and the donations
go up every year.

01:12.200 --> 01:14.191
Oh, parking's all set
for your friend, by the way.

01:14.240 --> 01:16.060
I just hope she brought
a big enough car.

01:16.840 --> 01:19.206
Are those bullet holes?

01:19.240 --> 01:21.572
Yeah, that used to belong
to Sherlock.

01:21.610 --> 01:24.340
Funny, you not telling me
he was dead.

01:24.380 --> 01:25.642
No one shot him.

01:25.680 --> 01:27.648
I think he was using that
in an experiment.

01:27.680 --> 01:30.717
He proved tweed isn't
bulletproof. He must be proud.

01:30.750 --> 01:33.253
Oh, Tammy!

01:33.290 --> 01:35.178
Hey!
Oh. Hey!

01:35.220 --> 01:36.357
I'll be right back.

01:36.390 --> 01:37.584
Mm-hmm.

01:37.630 --> 01:39.495
Joan.

01:39.530 --> 01:41.498
(laughing)

01:41.530 --> 01:42.497
Oh.

01:42.530 --> 01:44.418
Good to see you, too.

01:44.470 --> 01:48.395
Sorry, but someone wrote us
a check today-- a big one.

01:48.440 --> 01:50.135
Five zeroes big.

01:50.170 --> 01:51.467
Really?

01:51.510 --> 01:53.569
Really. And it is
all thanks to you.

01:53.610 --> 01:54.838
What are you talking about?

01:54.880 --> 01:56.370
The guy who
wrote the check,

01:56.410 --> 01:57.604
the guy who just
guaranteed

01:57.650 --> 01:58.844
we can keep Haven
up and running

01:58.880 --> 02:00.677
for at_ least the
next fIve years,

02:00.720 --> 02:03.518
he is a friend
of yours.

02:03.550 --> 02:05.780
VVho?
Morland Holmes.

02:05.820 --> 02:09.529
He... he is a friend
of yours, right?

02:11.260 --> 02:14.149
Yeah, that's a good question.

02:14.200 --> 02:15.849
You're the new guy.

02:15.900 --> 02:19.495
And for the new guy, every
day here starts the same way.

02:19.540 --> 02:20.598
At least in the winter.

02:20.640 --> 02:22.505
(metallic clanking)

02:22.540 --> 02:26.499
Attention, all bums, this is
your 6:00 am. wake-up call!

02:26.540 --> 02:29.509
Time to hit the road!

02:29.550 --> 02:31.506
See, they like the warm air

02:31.550 --> 02:32.949
that comes out
of this grate,

02:32.980 --> 02:35.540
but can't have a bunch
of homeless out front

02:35.580 --> 02:37.548
when the customers
start to show.

02:37.590 --> 02:40.354
Should I go back inside, maybe
get them some of the day-olds?

02:40.390 --> 02:41.652
What, you want
to encourage them?

02:41.690 --> 02:42.725
Hey, buddy.

02:42.760 --> 02:44.625
You deaf?

02:44.660 --> 02:47.652
You don't have to go home,
but you can't stay here.

02:47.700 --> 02:49.622
Hey!

02:49.670 --> 02:52.434
You got five seconds, then I'm
gonna tear that blanket off.

02:52.470 --> 02:54.233
I don't think
it's a blanket.

02:54.270 --> 02:57.239
It's, like, attached
to him, see?

02:57.270 --> 02:59.431
I think it's
a cape.

03:05.980 --> 03:07.777
*

03:13.990 --> 03:15.958
BELL:
Meet the Midnight Ranger.

03:15.990 --> 03:18.925
M.E. puts the time of death
around 11:00 last night.

03:18.960 --> 03:21.758
Body was found a little
before 6:00 this morning.

03:21.800 --> 03:24.667
Took someone seven hours
to find a dead body

03:24.700 --> 03:25.462
dressed like this?

03:25.500 --> 03:27.536
Well, either his cape
fell over him

03:27.570 --> 03:30.459
when he fell, or the person
who shot him tucked him in.

03:30.510 --> 03:31.807
To anyone who
walked by,

03:31.840 --> 03:33.933
he just looked like a homeless
guy trying to stay warm.

03:33.980 --> 03:35.572
Believe it or not,

03:35.610 --> 03:37.498
he wasn't coming home
from a costume party.

03:37.550 --> 03:39.643
These were his work
clothes-- sort of.

03:39.680 --> 03:41.443
He walked a beat
In Greenpomt

03:41.480 --> 03:43.516
almost every night.

03:43.550 --> 03:45.711
Real-life superhero.

03:45.750 --> 03:47.957
One of a subculture of

03:47.990 --> 03:52.290
ordinary men and women
who don costumes to perform acts

03:52.330 --> 03:53.649
of public service.

03:53.700 --> 03:55.622
I'm familiar with
the phenomenon,

03:55.660 --> 03:57.366
though I've never
delved too deeply

03:57.400 --> 03:59.994
into the affairs of the heroes
who operate in New York.

04:00.040 --> 04:01.769
They mostly
just scold litterbugs

04:01.800 --> 04:03.665
and help little old ladies
across the street.

04:03.710 --> 04:05.962
Mm, some of them
fight crime, too.

04:06.010 --> 04:07.432
The Midnight Ranger
liked to hassle

04:07.480 --> 04:08.674
street level
drug dealers.

04:08.710 --> 04:10.803
Even chased down a
purse-snatcher or two.

04:10.850 --> 04:13.444
Well, obviously he got in
over his head last night.

04:13.480 --> 04:15.448
Or someone came
looking for him.

04:15.480 --> 04:17.414
The shooter used
armor-piercmg rounds.

04:17.450 --> 04:19.509
Considering the Midnight
Ranger wore armor,

04:19.560 --> 04:21.289
it's possible
he was targeted.

04:21.320 --> 04:23.754
Maybe by someone he
tangled with in the past.

04:23.790 --> 04:26.623
You keep using his hero name,
the Midnight Ranger.

04:26.660 --> 04:28.457
That's 'cause
I have to.

04:28.500 --> 04:29.819
There wasn't any
ID. on the body.

04:29.870 --> 04:31.622
That's why I called;
thought maybe you could

04:31.670 --> 04:33.297
help figure out his
secret identity.

04:34.670 --> 04:36.706
This is an impressive suit.

04:36.740 --> 04:38.605
Indeed.

04:38.640 --> 04:40.835
If you look closely,
you'll see the button holes,

04:40.880 --> 04:43.542
which attach the cape
to the shoulder armor,

04:43.580 --> 04:44.569
are tailor-made.

04:44.610 --> 04:46.669
Not homemade or factory made.

04:46.720 --> 04:49.075
They're straight-cut
and hand sewn by an expert.

04:49.120 --> 04:51.918
Now, given that the
Midnight Ranger's territory

04:51.950 --> 04:53.554
was Greenpoint,

04:53.590 --> 04:54.784
perhaps you should visit

04:54.820 --> 04:56.788
some of the neighborhood
tailors, dry cleaners.

04:56.830 --> 04:58.752
There might be a seamstress
or a sempster

04:58.790 --> 04:59.791
who knows his real identity.

04:59.830 --> 05:01.627
Watson and I,
meanwhile,

05:01.660 --> 05:05.460
will adjourn to the New York
offices of Superlative Comics.

05:05.500 --> 05:06.364
What for?

05:06.400 --> 05:08.664
Well, unlike
his civic-minded brethren,

05:08.700 --> 05:09.837
our victim

05:09.870 --> 05:12.100
did not come up
with his own

05:12.140 --> 05:13.539
superhero name and costume.

05:13.580 --> 05:14.933
Rather, he assumed the identity

05:14.980 --> 05:18.370
of a character owned
and copyrighted by Superlative.

05:18.410 --> 05:19.718
I know. I used to read

05:19.750 --> 05:21.809
the Midnight Ranger
when I was a kid.

05:21.850 --> 05:24.045
Do you seriously think
this guy got gunned down

05:24.090 --> 05:25.739
by an angry
comic book company?

05:25.790 --> 05:27.712
No, but Superlative
were none too happy

05:27.760 --> 05:29.113
about the infringement,

05:29.160 --> 05:30.855
and they've been
trying to find out

05:30.890 --> 05:32.858
the Midnight Ranger's identity
for well over a year.

05:34.560 --> 05:36.892
So they might know
more about him than we do.

05:36.930 --> 05:38.898
HOLMES: Well, it makes
a certain amount of sense

05:38.930 --> 05:40.966
that our John Doe would emulate
the Midnight Ranger,

05:41.000 --> 05:43.639
as opposed to other heroes
in the Superlative library.

05:43.670 --> 05:45.831
The Ranger has
no real superpowers.

05:45.870 --> 05:47.804
He is simply
an Olympic-level athlete

05:47.840 --> 05:49.546
with an obscenely high IQ

05:49.580 --> 05:51.047
who, for some reason,
remains oblivious

05:51.080 --> 05:53.674
to the lure of the Olympic games
and the Nobel Prize.

05:53.720 --> 05:56.143
He didn't dedicate himself
to crime-fighting, however,

05:56.180 --> 05:57.989
until his fiance, Rebecca
Rogers, was murdered by...

05:58.020 --> 06:00.682
You really think
I don't know the origin

06:00.720 --> 06:02.017
of the Midnight Ranger?

06:03.790 --> 06:05.451
My brother was a geek, remember?

06:05.490 --> 06:07.651
I know the origins of
all of the Superlative heroes.

06:07.700 --> 06:09.565
Really?
Really.

06:11.030 --> 06:13.931
Exposed to theta radiation
by his scientist parents.

06:15.500 --> 06:18.060
Stung by
a radioactive scorpion.

06:18.110 --> 06:21.136
Uh, nuclear power plant
explosion.

06:21.180 --> 06:23.842
In what universe are these
people not all dead from cancer?

06:23.880 --> 06:25.700
When's the last time
you heard from your father?

06:25.750 --> 06:27.069
It's been a few months. Why?

06:27.120 --> 06:28.519
_ MAN:
MISS Watson.

06:28.550 --> 06:30.017
Uh, Mr. Holmes.

06:31.490 --> 06:33.481
Al Baxter. I edit
the Midnight Ranger book.

06:33.520 --> 06:35.784
I was told you have
questions about him.

06:35.820 --> 06:38.459
We do have questions,
just not about your Ranger.

06:38.490 --> 06:41.550
The flesh and blood Midnight
Ranger was shot dead last night.

06:41.600 --> 06:43.818
Unfortunately, the bullets used
were not radioactive,

06:43.870 --> 06:45.690
so he'll be remaining
quite dead.

06:45.730 --> 06:46.936
Oh.

06:46.970 --> 06:49.734
I got no idea
who this guy is.

06:49.770 --> 06:51.863
You got any idea
who this guy is?

06:51.910 --> 06:53.832
I knew something like
this would happen.

06:53.880 --> 06:56.576
As soon as this idiot started
operating a couple years back,

06:56.610 --> 06:57.770
I said to my guys,

06:57.810 --> 06:59.869
we got two
possible outcomes:

06:59.920 --> 07:00.841
he hurts someone

07:00.880 --> 07:02.711
or someone hurts him.

07:02.750 --> 07:03.785
Either way,

07:03.820 --> 07:04.844
it gets us
all the wrong headlines.

07:04.890 --> 07:06.778
At the worst possible time.

07:06.820 --> 07:08.788
What do you mean?
EICHORN: We sent our lawyers

07:08.820 --> 07:10.185
after the real Ranger

07:10.230 --> 07:11.857
because we had to protect
our licensing deals.

07:11.890 --> 07:13.949
But now we're in talks

07:14.000 --> 07:16.491
with a studio about
a major motIon picture.

07:16.530 --> 07:19.738
So we finally get our slice
of that superhero movie cake,

07:19.770 --> 07:21.089
made from layers of money.

07:21.140 --> 07:23.506
For a character whose book
is hardly selling?

07:23.540 --> 07:25.599
This is a reimagining.

07:25.640 --> 07:28.575
A new Midnight Ranger,
relevant to today's society.

07:28.610 --> 07:30.077
Sandy means darker,
more violent.

07:30.110 --> 07:32.772
Could the death of the real
Ranger affect the deal?

07:32.820 --> 07:33.912
It can't help.

07:33.950 --> 07:35.645
But on the plus side,

07:35.680 --> 07:37.238
the picture wouldn't be
in theaters for at least

07:37.290 --> 07:38.746
a couple more years.

07:38.790 --> 07:40.587
Any luck,

07:40.620 --> 07:41.882
this real Ranger mishegas

07:41.920 --> 07:43.785
will be squarely
in our rearview mirror.

07:44.830 --> 07:46.627
You said
you wanted everything

07:46.660 --> 07:47.922
our investigators
turned up.

07:47.960 --> 07:49.222
You got it.

07:49.260 --> 07:51.262
But I'll tell you
right now, it isn't much.

07:51.300 --> 07:52.767
Your dead guy's
real superpower,

07:52.800 --> 07:53.937
turns out,
was being able

07:53.970 --> 07:56.131
to run faster than people
trying to serve him papers.

07:56.170 --> 07:57.967
We got some
blurry pictures,

07:58.010 --> 08:01.901
an idea of where his regular
patrol was, that's it.

08:01.940 --> 08:03.874
We'll take whatever you've got.

08:04.910 --> 08:07.219
Yeah, that's my stitching.

08:07.250 --> 08:09.844
I'd like to show you a picture
of the man who got killed.

08:09.890 --> 08:10.845
You won't see

08:10.890 --> 08:12.551
anything graphic, just the face.

08:12.590 --> 08:13.887
That be okay?

08:13.920 --> 08:15.888
(sighs):
All right. Yeah.

08:20.730 --> 08:22.891
(sighs):
That's him.

08:22.930 --> 08:24.898
That's definitely him.

08:24.930 --> 08:26.898
Do you know his name?

08:26.940 --> 08:30.865
You know, there used to be a lot
of crime in this neighborhood.

08:30.910 --> 08:33.276
Did you know that?

08:33.310 --> 08:37.849
Back in 2010, we were held up
twice in the same month.

08:37.880 --> 08:39.871
Twice.
By the same guy.

08:39.920 --> 08:41.273
Cops never caught him.

08:44.220 --> 08:46.279
I never_saw _
the Ranger In actIon.

08:46.320 --> 08:49.209
I mean, it's not like he drove
around is a Midnight Mobile.

08:49.260 --> 08:51.228
But I'm telling you,

08:51.260 --> 08:53.558
last couple of years,
things got better.

08:53.600 --> 08:55.227
People felt safer.

08:55.260 --> 08:57.262
He didn't want anybody
to know his real name,

08:57.300 --> 08:59.564
so, uh, why should
I tell you?

08:59.600 --> 09:01.989
Because you don't want
the person who did this

09:02.040 --> 09:03.837
to get away with murder.

09:07.910 --> 09:09.639
(sighs)

09:09.680 --> 09:12.979
His name was Danny.
Danny Dalton.

09:13.020 --> 09:15.318
That's the real
Midnight Ranger's name.

09:15.350 --> 09:17.113
I mean,

09:17.150 --> 09:20.051
the real real one, the original,
the one from the comics.

09:20.090 --> 09:23.821
He might as well have told you
his name was Bruce Wayne.

09:23.860 --> 09:25.350
Well, I'm sorry, but that's...

09:25.390 --> 09:28.689
that's the only name
he ever gave me.

09:32.100 --> 09:33.988
(door opens)

09:36.100 --> 09:38.261
Mr. Holmes.

09:39.340 --> 09:41.001
Joan.

09:41.040 --> 09:43.247
To what do I owe the pleasure?

09:43.280 --> 09:44.907
I came to say thank you.

09:44.950 --> 09:46.713
Unless there's another
Morland Holmes

09:46.750 --> 09:49.719
who donated $250,000 to Haven
for the Homeless yesterday.

09:49.750 --> 09:51.741
(speaking Russian)

10:01.730 --> 10:03.789
I must confess,

10:03.830 --> 10:07.095
I was motivated in part
by the American tax system.

10:07.140 --> 10:08.368
It was a good year.

10:08.400 --> 10:10.106
The money
had to go somewhere,

10:10.140 --> 10:11.869
and your charity seemed

10:11.910 --> 10:13.901
a better final destination
than the government.

10:13.940 --> 10:15.271
You want something.

10:15.310 --> 10:16.868
I was going to wait

10:16.910 --> 10:18.377
a decent interval
between the donation

10:18.410 --> 10:19.911
and asking for your help,

10:19.950 --> 10:22.168
but, in fact, I'm in need
of an investigator.

10:22.220 --> 10:24.939
You have in-house investigators.
I do.

10:24.990 --> 10:28.289
But it's the sanctity of
my house that I'm worried about.

10:28.320 --> 10:30.880
What's the problem?

10:30.930 --> 10:32.693
Please.

10:39.130 --> 10:42.099
As you may
or may not know,

10:42.140 --> 10:45.007
oil has been discovered
in the Colombian jungle.

10:45.040 --> 10:46.928
A group
of Chinese investors

10:46.980 --> 10:49.801
hired me to broker a deal
with the Colombian government

10:49.850 --> 10:52.239
to allow for the construction
of several refInerIes.

10:52.280 --> 10:55.078
After a year
of painstaking work,

10:55.120 --> 10:57.816
one of my competitors swooped in

10:57.850 --> 10:59.954
and closed the deal
in a weekend.

10:59.990 --> 11:03.050
And you think someone here
helped them undercut you.

11:03.090 --> 11:07.151
I had a team of ten assisting me
with the negotiations.

11:07.200 --> 11:10.124
Each person had access
to technical specifications,

11:10.170 --> 11:12.229
cost projections,
any number of things

11:12.270 --> 11:16.161
that would make it simple for a
competitor to beat our numbers.

11:16.200 --> 11:19.169
Does anyone jump out at you?

11:19.210 --> 11:22.941
They're a good group.

11:22.980 --> 11:25.403
Each person
was vetted meticulously

11:25.450 --> 11:27.247
before they came to work here.

11:27.280 --> 11:30.181
Isn't it possible
that your competitor

11:30.220 --> 11:32.017
just did a better job than you?

11:32.050 --> 11:33.779
It is.

11:33.820 --> 11:36.050
In fact, nothing
would make me happier

11:36.090 --> 11:37.853
than knowing that

11:37.890 --> 11:40.256
I can trust the ten individuals
In questIon.

11:40.300 --> 11:42.120
Why me?

11:42.160 --> 11:44.060
Why not ask
Sherlock for help?

11:44.100 --> 11:47.467
Sherlock and I are not
on the best of terms at present.

11:50.110 --> 11:52.032
I'll think about it.

11:52.070 --> 11:54.868
If it's a problem...

11:54.910 --> 11:56.741
I do understand.

11:56.780 --> 11:58.270
It's pretty hard
to say no to someone

11:58.310 --> 12:00.119
who just donated
a quarter of a million dollars

12:00.150 --> 12:01.742
to a charity I care about.

12:01.780 --> 12:04.817
Well, that was the
whole point, right?

12:09.220 --> 12:10.881
(door opens)

12:11.990 --> 12:13.321
(door closes)

12:16.000 --> 12:17.524
What's all that?

12:17.570 --> 12:19.526
I wondered if some enlightenment
might be found

12:19.570 --> 12:21.128
in the fictional universe

12:21.170 --> 12:23.161
our Midnight Ranger
took inspiration from.

12:23.210 --> 12:25.337
So I reached out to the
Midnight Ranger fan community,

12:25.370 --> 12:27.099
and, with their help,
I managed to procure

12:27.140 --> 12:28.129
the comic's entire run.

12:30.080 --> 12:32.275
There has to be,
what, 600 issues?

12:32.310 --> 12:34.449
648, to be precise.

12:34.480 --> 12:38.439
Having read the bulk of them,
I confess I do see the appeal.

12:38.490 --> 12:41.152
If you strip away
the silly outfits, square jaws

12:41.190 --> 12:42.828
and skull-sized breasts,

12:42.860 --> 12:45.181
there is a cardinal devotion
to justIce.

12:45.230 --> 12:49.098
The attention to continuity,
however, is laughable.

12:49.130 --> 12:51.894
This is the tenth
issue from the 19405,

12:51.930 --> 12:53.898
and you took it
out of its bag.

12:53.940 --> 12:57.068
Yes._How else _
was I gomg to read It?

12:57.110 --> 12:58.566
(groans)

12:58.610 --> 13:00.999
And you did
all this why?

13:01.040 --> 13:04.077
Over the course of the 80 years
of his derring-do,

13:04.110 --> 13:06.078
the Midnight Ranger has died

13:06.110 --> 13:08.078
five times.

